  "AI content payment is not merely a copyright or transaction-efficiency problem; it is a question of political-economic legitimacy. As AI valuations reach hundreds of billions, society asks why the gains from public web content and human knowledge accrue to a few firms. The paper proposes a six-layer tiered data market — from free public content through scarce verified datasets to public benefit-sharing — and defines the AI network democratic economy: rights, pricing, participation, auditability, and returns, each democratized through machine-readable protocols like AICR/AICL.": "Tefo ya diteng tsa AI hase feela bothata ba tokelo ya bongodi kapa bokgoni ba dikgwebo; ke potso ya bonnete ba dipolotiki-le-moruo. Ha boleng ba AI bo fihla dibilioune tse makgolo, sechaba se botsa hore na ke hobaneng melemo e tswang diteng tse phatlalatsang tsa Web le tsebo ya batho e fumanwa ke difeme tse fokolang. Pampiri ena e sisinya mmaraka wa data o nang le mekgahlelo e tsheletseng — ho tloha diteng tsa mahala tsa setjhaba, ho tsamaea ka dataseta tse fokolang tse netefaditsweng, ho isa ho arolelano ya melemo ya setjhaba — mme e hlalosa moruo wa marang-rang wa demokrasi wa AI: litokelo, ho beha theko, ho nka karolo, bokgoni ba ho hlahlojwa, le meputso, tse ka nngwe e tsamaiswang ka demokrasi ka diprotokolo tse balehang ke mochini tse kang AICR/AICL.",
